    ax.set_xlabel(col[i])
    ax.set_title('Disease by '+col[i])
    ax.set_xticks(x)
    ax.set_xticklabels(dist_data.index)
    ax.legend()

    fig.add_subplot(ax)

fig.show()

#fucntions to map the different features

def BMI(x):
    if x<18.5:
        return 'underweight'
    elif  18.5<=x<25:
        return 'normal'
    elif  25<=x<30:
        return 'overweight'
    else:
        return 'obese'
    

def Age_Group(x):
    if x<45:
        return 'young'
    elif  45<=x<65:
        return 'old'
    
def HighBP_Group(x):
    if x<120:
        return 'normal'
    elif 120<=x<130:
        return 'elevated'
    elif 130<=x<140:
        return 'high'
    else:
        return 'hypertension'

    
def LowBP_Group(x):
    if x<80:
        return 'normal'
    elif 80<=x<89:
        return 'high'
    else:
        return 'hypertension'

Lets plot the ROC curve for our final model¶
Since we want to compare model performances, lets make a function to plot ROC for all the models we run so that there is no repitition of code¶
In [38]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score
def plot_rocs(pred_prob):
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--') 
    plt.axis([0, 1, 0, 1])
    
    for model, values in pred_prob.items():
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(values[1],values[0][:,1])
        auc = round(roc_auc_score(values[1],values[0][:,1])*100,2)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=2, label="%s Classifier : AUC = %0.2f" % (model,auc))
    
    plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (Fall-Out)', fontsize=16) 
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Recall)', fontsize=16)  
    plt.title('ROC Curve for Classifiers ')
    plt.show()

# storing the prediction probabilities in a dictionary for future use

pred_prob={}
